ailability of geographical knowledge, the material conditions of travel, and the variety of destinations that sought to profit from visitors with money to spend. Entrepreneurs began to transform the critical steps of travel—deciding where to go and how to get there—into commodities that could be produced in volume and sold to a marketplace of consumers. The identities of Americans prosperous enough to afford such commodities were fundamentally changed as they came to define themselves through the consumption of experiences.Mackintosh ultimately demonstrates that the cultural values and market forces surrounding tourism in the early nineteenth century continue to shape our experience of travel to this day.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aPopular culturezUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aPopular culture-United States-History-19th century. 0aTourismxSocial aspectszUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aTourism-Social aspects-United States-History-19th century. 0aTouristszUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aTourists-United States-History-19th century. 0aTravelerszUnited Statesy19th century. 0aTravelers-United States-History-19th century. 7aHISTORY / United States / 19th Century.2bisacsh  abook history.  aboosters.  acapitalism.  acaricatures.  acommodification.  acommodified experience.  adestinations.  aentrepreneurs.  ageographical knowledge.  aguidebooks.  aleisure.  amarket economy.  amutually constituted.  aobservation.  apicturesque.  asatirists.  ascientific publication.  atickets.  atourism.  atourist industry.  atransatlantic.  atransportation.  atravel.  atraveler.  atravelers.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z97831107227270 cprintz978147988937240uhttps://d